<paragraph blockId="30.[212,504,312,336]" box="[212,504,312,336]" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[212,504,312,336]" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">The amoena species group</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="605" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="30.[212,1172,401,719]" box="[212,320,401,424]" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">
<heading box="[212,320,401,424]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[212,320,401,424]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[212,1172,401,719]" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">
The amoena species group includes 
<emphasis box="[627,1077,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">
<taxonomicName box="[627,759,440,463]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amoena">M. amoena</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[773,900,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chaperi">M. chaperi</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos &amp; Silveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[913,1077,440,463]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guimaraesi">M. guimaraesi</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Santos &amp; Melo, 2014" authorityName="Santos &amp; Melo" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mura" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">M. mura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[277,338,472,495]" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Its species can be recognized by the following characters: posterior upper margin of metepisternum modified into a conspicuously large process covered with velvety pilosity, its diameter at least 0.75× the tegula length (except in the female of 
<taxonomicName box="[212,339,568,591]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amoena">
<emphasis box="[212,339,568,591]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">M. amoena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); male E3 centrally in the apex with sinuous notch adjacent to expanded area of sternum (
<figureCitation box="[409,558,599,623]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="14.[212,279,1395,1417]" captionTargetBox="[213,1170,168,1363]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[213,1170,168,1364]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 8. Males of Megalopta. (A‒C) Ventral view of sternum 3‒4; (A) M. chaperi Vachal Amajari, Brazil; (B) M. amoena Spinola from Alenquer, Brazil; (C) M. mura sp. n. from Parauapebas, Brazil; (D, E) Dorsal view of posterior surface of F6‒F11; (D) M. sulciventris Friese from Manaus, Brazil; (E) M. aegis Vachal from Parauapebas, Brazil; (F) dorsal view of flagellum of M. amoena from Alenquer, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004475/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">
Figure 8A 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[526,539,599,623]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">‒</emphasis>
C
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[212,1172,401,719]" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">
<taxonomicName box="[254,380,632,655]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amoena">
<emphasis box="[254,380,632,655]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">M. amoena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed (
<figureCitation box="[630,760,631,655]" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="23.[144,211,1560,1582]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1528]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[144,1104,168,1528]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figure 14. Distribution records of Megalopta species. (A) M. aegis Vachal (grey circles) and M. aeneicollis Friese (black squares); (B) M. nitidicollis Friese; (C) M. sulciventris Friese; (D) M. amoena Spinola." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004487" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004487/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">Figure 14D</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[784,905,631,655]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chaperi">
<emphasis box="[784,905,631,655]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">M. chaperi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to north of the 
<collectingRegion box="[255,374,663,687]" country="Venezuela" name="Amazonas" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
and Negro rivers (
<figureCitation box="[596,726,663,687]" captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="31.[144,211,1560,1582]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1528]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[144,1104,168,1528]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="Figure 15. Distribution records of Megalopta species. (A) M. chaperi Vachal; (B) M. guimaraesi Santos &amp; Silveira (black circles) and M. mura sp. n. (grey squares); (C) M. piraha sp. n (grey squares) and M. yanomami sp. n. (black circles); (D) M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira (grey square), M. guarani sp. n (triangle), M. xavante sp. n (hexagon), M. karitiana sp. n (black circle), M. mapinguari sp. n (black square) and M. purpurata Smith (grey circle)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004489/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">Figure 15A</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos &amp; Silveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[751,913,664,687]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guimaraesi">
<emphasis box="[751,913,664,687]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">M. guimaraesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the Atlantic Forest and Cerrado and 
<taxonomicName authority="Santos &amp; Melo, 2014" authorityName="Santos &amp; Melo" authorityYear="2014" box="[415,514,695,719]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mura" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[415,441,696,719]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[457,514,696,719]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">mura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[523,585,695,718]" pageId="30" pageNumber="605" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
to north-western South America (
<figureCitation box="[979,1106,694,718]" captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="31.[144,211,1560,1582]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1528]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[144,1104,168,1528]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="Figure 15. Distribution records of Megalopta species. (A) M. chaperi Vachal; (B) M. guimaraesi Santos &amp; Silveira (black circles) and M. mura sp. n. (grey squares); (C) M. piraha sp. n (grey squares) and M. yanomami sp. n. (black circles); (D) M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira (grey square), M. guarani sp. n (triangle), M. xavante sp. n (hexagon), M. karitiana sp. n (black circle), M. mapinguari sp. n (black square) and M. purpurata Smith (grey circle)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004489/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="605">Figure 15B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
